  <li><strong>Look for Right Bank Bordeaux for Ultimate Expression</strong> - The best Merlots come from Pomerol and Saint-Émilion, where clay-rich soils create wines with unmatched depth and complexity. Château Pétrus and Le Pin represent Merlot's pinnacle, while Château Canon and Figeac offer exceptional quality at more accessible prices. These wines showcase Merlot's true potential with their signature velvet texture and mineral backbone.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Serve at Precisely 60-65°F for Optimal Fruit Expression</strong> - Unlike Cabernet Sauvignon which can handle warmer temperatures, the best Merlots shine when served slightly cooler to preserve their delicate fruit aromatics and prevent the alcohol from overwhelming the wine's elegant structure. This temperature range allows the characteristic plum and black cherry notes to emerge without masking the subtle earthiness.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Decant Young Merlots for 30-60 Minutes, Skip for Aged Bottles</strong> - Premium Merlots under 8 years old benefit from brief decanting to soften tannins and open up the bouquet, but older bottles (15+ years) should be opened and served immediately as extended air exposure can cause rapid deterioration of the delicate tertiary aromas like truffle and leather that make aged Merlot so special.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Choose Burgundy-Style Glasses for Maximum Aromatics</strong> - The best Merlots reveal their complexity in glasses with a wide bowl and tapered rim, similar to those used for Pinot Noir. This shape concentrates the wine's subtle floral notes (violet, rose petal) and allows the medium-weight structure to show its elegance rather than being overwhelmed by a large Bordeaux glass.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Peak Drinking Window is 8-15 Years for Top Estates</strong> - While Right Bank Bordeaux can age for decades, the best Merlots typically reach their sweet spot between 8-15 years when primary fruit integrates with secondary characteristics. At this stage, you'll experience the perfect balance of ripe plum, cedar, tobacco, and that signature Merlot silkiness without losing freshness.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Identify Quality by the "Merlot Handshake"</strong> - The best Merlots have a distinctive tactile quality - they coat your palate with a velvety, almost creamy texture while maintaining freshness. This comes from perfectly ripe tannins and balanced acidity. Avoid bottles that feel thin or overly jammy, as these indicate either underripe fruit or overextraction during winemaking.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Store Horizontally at 55°F with 70% Humidity</strong> - Premium Merlots are particularly sensitive to temperature fluctuations due to their medium body and delicate structure. Consistent cool storage prevents premature oxidation of the wine's signature fruit-forward character, while proper humidity keeps corks from drying out and allowing air to spoil the wine's elegant profile.</li>
  
