<p>Young Merlot showcases vibrant <strong>primary fruit flavors</strong> of plum and blackberry with firm tannins. After 5-7 years, <strong>secondary characteristics</strong> emerge—leather, cedar, and tobacco notes develop as tannins soften and integrate. <strong>Tertiary complexity</strong> appears after a decade, revealing earthy truffle, dried herbs, and mineral nuances while fruit transitions from fresh to preserved.</p>

<h3>Optimal Storage Conditions</h3>

<p>Store bottles horizontally at <strong>55-60°F (13-16°C)</strong> with 60-70% humidity to prevent cork drying. Maintain consistent temperature—fluctuations cause expansion and contraction that can damage seals. Keep wines in <strong>dark conditions</strong> away from vibration, as Merlot's delicate fruit compounds are particularly sensitive to light degradation.</p>

<h3>Aging vs. Spoilage Indicators</h3>

<p><strong>Proper aging signs:</strong> Color shifts from purple-ruby to garnet-brick, sediment formation increases, and cork shows wine staining without crumbling. <strong>Spoilage warnings:</strong> Musty cork odors, excessive ullage (low fill level), or crystalline deposits on cork surfaces indicate potential problems.</p>

