    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Right Bank and Left Bank Bordeaux Merlot?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Right Bank Bordeaux Merlot (from Pomerol and Saint-Émilion) is typically more plush, fruit-forward, and Merlot-dominant, with silky tannins and notes of plum and chocolate. Left Bank Merlot is usually blended with more Cabernet Sauvignon, creating firmer structure, cassis flavors, and greater aging potential. Right Bank expressions like Château Pétrus showcase Merlot's elegance, while Left Bank wines use Merlot to soften Cabernet's intensity.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Merlot a good wine for beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, Merlot is excellent for wine beginners due to its approachable, fruit-forward character and soft tannins that don't create the astringent sensation found in Cabernet Sauvignon. The grape's natural tendency toward plum, cherry, and chocolate flavors makes it immediately appealing without requiring extensive palate development. Quality examples from Washington State or entry-level Bordeaux provide complexity without intimidation, making Merlot an ideal bridge wine for developing more sophisticated tastes.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve premium Merlot?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve premium Merlot at 60-65°F (15-18°C), slightly cooler than room temperature but warmer than typical refrigeration. This temperature range allows the wine's fruit complexity to shine while maintaining proper tannin structure. If the wine feels too warm, it will taste overly alcoholic and flabby; too cold, and you'll miss the nuanced aromatics and the wine will taste thin and harsh.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I age the best Merlot wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Top-tier Merlot from Pomerol, Saint-Émilion, or premium Napa Valley can age 15-25 years, developing tertiary flavors of leather, earth, and dried fruits. Washington State Merlot typically peaks at 8-12 years, while most commercial Merlot is best consumed within 3-5 years of release. The key indicators for aging potential are concentrated fruit, balanced acidity, and quality tannin structure from producers like Château Le Pin or Duckhorn Vineyards.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when buying Merlot?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is avoiding Merlot entirely due to the "Sideways effect" or assuming all Merlot is simple and sweet. Many consumers also confuse mass-produced, over-oaked California Merlot with quality expressions from regions like Walla Walla or Bordeaux. Another common error is serving Merlot too warm, which masks its elegant fruit character and makes it taste heavy and alcoholic.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which regions offer the best value in Merlot?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Washington State's Columbia Valley provides exceptional Merlot value, offering Bordeaux-style complexity at a fraction of French prices, with producers like Chateau Ste. Michelle and L'Ecole No 41. Chile's Colchagua Valley delivers excellent everyday Merlot with good concentration and varietal character for under $20. Right Bank Bordeaux satellites like Lalande-de-Pomerol offer authentic French terroir expression at more accessible prices than the famous appellations.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wines are similar to Merlot if I want to explore other varieties?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">If you enjoy Merlot's soft, fruit-forward style, try Grenache from Châteauneuf-du-Pape or Spanish Garnacha for similar plushness with more spice. Carménère from Chile offers comparable texture with herbaceous complexity, while Malbec from Argentina provides the same approachable tannins but with darker fruit and more intensity. For something closer to Bordeaux-style Merlot, explore Cabernet Franc from Loire Valley, which shares Merlot's elegance but with more pronounced herbal notes.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibond text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I identify a high-quality Merlot by the label?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for specific vineyard designations or small-lot indicators rather than generic regional appellations, as quality Merlot producers emphasize terroir expression. Premium Merlot labels often mention harvest dates, specific blocks, or winemaker signatures, indicating hands-on production. Avoid wines with cartoon labels or overly promotional language like "smooth and mellow" – serious Merlot producers focus on vineyard and vintage information rather than marketing speak.</p>
